<seg id="2981">All settings are stored in $KDEHOME / config / ksysvrc. presets will be removed from the global file ($KDEDIR / share / config / ksysvrc) if available. otherwise they will be saved by & ksysv; otherwise changes to the default settings are saved in a local ksysvrc.</seg>
<seg id="2982">"" "" "" "I have experimented with the standard runlevel, and now the machine starts constantly. what can I do?" "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2983">"" "" "" "on the LILO prompt, type linux single and press the input key to start in the single user mode. then edit the / etc / inittab file and change the default runlevel to a reasonable value (3 should normally be fine)." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2984">"" "" "" "I have provided some system services with & ksysv; for execution under runlevel X, but they are not executed." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2985">"" "" "" "if you use & SuSE; or Delix (DLD), you need to edit additional files in / etc, which are only available in these distributions." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2986">"" "" "" "the way system services are started in these distributions, simplifies configuration for the proprietary setup programs of these distributions, but unfortunately does not correspond to any standard. authors of & ksysv; plan an extension of the program for this approach." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2987">"" "" "" "if you are using another distribution, please check if all configuration files are available (and also see if they are in the right directory). some services (such as & eg; Apache and httpd) just quit without a message if their configuration files are not present or configured wrongly." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2988">"" "" "" "the importance of the & Linux; -runlevel varies from distribution to distribution, may even be different from version to version. if you use a different distribution, please send me information about the runlevel so that this manual can be added." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2989">"" "" "" "this documentation refers to & kuser; 1.0. with this program, you can manage the users and groups of your system." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2990">"" "" "" "to begin with & kuser; to start, it is sufficient to read the chapters adaptation of & kuser; to start reading." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2991">"" "" "" "after you have made changes, you need to save them. either use the corresponding toolbar icon or the Save in the File menu." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2992">"" "" "" "the main window consists of two card cards, the user and the user group list. to edit, select the desired user or group with a double click on the entry." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2993">"" "" "" "some card cards are only displayed if you have enabled advanced system settings. only if you have limited space restrictions (quota) for users, you can create additional cards if shadow passwords, etc / master.passwd, as in BSD-Unixes." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2994">"" "" "" "the card password management appears, if shadow passwords or e.g. / etc / master.passwd are installed as in BSD-Unix." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2995">This card only appears if for at least a built-in filesystem space limitation (quota) is enabled and initialized (see the file quota parameter in the file system).</seg>
<seg id="2996">"" "" "" "these parameters can be set individually for each file system. the current file system is selected using the field file system, with limited space limitation." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2997">"" "" "" "the card card group informs about the group affiliations of the selected user. the default group, which the user owns, can be found in the Primaries section." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2998">"" "" "" "to add a user to the group, select this user in the list." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="2999">"" "" "" "to add a user or group, select Add from the user or group menu or click on the appropriate addition button of the toolbar. editing or deleting the selected user or group works analogously." "" "" ""</seg>
<seg id="3000">"" "" "" "with this module you can install the LILO boot manager, remove and change the boot password, add time to boot of the standard operating system, remove, modify operating systems, remove, change and more." "" "" ""</seg>
